<br>
The principle of MAD, or Mutually Assured Destruction, is that if one country uses nukes, the other country will retaliate, and both countries are dust, one just sticks around 45 minutes longer than the other.<br>
<br>
North Korea, regardless of posturing, will not attack the US with an atomic weapon.  Even the most impassioned extremist can see that if they attack us with their pool of 6 atomic weapons, we'll attack them with our pool of what, 12,000 nuclear weapons?  Attacking the US would be suicide, which is why they won't do it.<br>
<br>
Now, the problem lies in the fact that one of those nukes might leave NK and go somewhere else.  That's a problem.  If the US is hit by a terrorrist attack using a nuclear weapon, it's hard to prove (the bomb itself is basically vaporized), and we have a hard time nuking someone back.  That's why we don't like NK having nukes, because we don't know what they may end up doing with them.  <br>
<br>
That said, I think it's a pretty safe bet that at some point in the next 40 years, there's going to be a low-yield nuclear device detonated in a population center of the continental United States.  By NK building nukes, the odds of that happening by some means has increased. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=merraharvaz>MerraharVaz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 396<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/3/03 2:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=219.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re: Hmmm</span><hr size=1> Anika always scares me when he talks about nukes =| <p>---------------<br>
The dorf formerly known as Merrahar...</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=amourbien>Amourbien</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 70<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/3/03 6:47 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=219.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re: Hmmm</span><hr size=1> It is a given that as the world moves forward in history, additinional countries will attain nuclear capability.  Once technology is discovered it is impossible to undo it even one as destructive as the nuclear issue.<br>
<br>
The key has to be somehow to make it so undesirable to produce these weapons that countries will not want to bother.  On the upswing possession of nuclear weapons immediately vaults a nation (currently) into a sort of club.  If a country is known to possess a nuclear weapon another country will not attack or provoke it directly.  It is my belief that is why North Korea has been working so hard on this.  The nation is an extremely paranoid place, and when Bush gave his speech it really created a sort of conniption fit in NK.<br>
<br>
At this point in time, I don't think even diplomacy will stop NK from producing these weapons now that they are so close.  The solution has become very difficult now.  With NK likely to have weapons produced within a month or three after all the efforts put into their program is probably not going to see a cesation of efforts therein.  Economic and diplomatic sanctions won't really have an affect on a country used to such miseries.  I think for the time being a more open dialouge with them would be a very good thing.  Let the NKoreans know that we do not intend to attack but that we will not broker any provocations on their part either.<br>
<br>
As for NK selling weapons..there have been many shipments of missile parts, military computer technologies, etc intercepted as these ships were heading to destinations unknown.  Most of the Iraqi arsenal was American-made (from the time of the Iran/Iraq War) but lately their weapons' technology has come from NK most notably missile improvements.  To this day NK still exports such parts as it is highly profitable and quite frankly they need every hard bit of currency they can get.  Will NK sell nuclear technology?  If past is any indication of peformance then the answer would be yes.<br>
<br>
