<br>
Anyway, yeah, before I bought this condo, I actually looked at the blast radii for different strengths of nuclear weapons, and figured out how far north of downtown Cincinnati would be 'safe' in the worst-case-scenario, and figured out that 18 miles was good enough.<br>
<br>
Of course, who the hell would nuke Cincinnati, unless someone decided to rid us of the orange and black scourge of humanity known as the Bengals.<br>
<br>
Still, when and if I buy another house, it'll probably be a bit further from a major population center.  Am I living scared?  Nah.  But no reason to take chances - besides I detest urban areas, even though I'm going to make a long desired tourist trip to NYC in a couple of weeks.  <br>
<br>
My own non-scientific estimate is that there's a 70-80% chance of someone detonating a nuke somewhere in the US, most likely in NYC, Washington DC, LA, or Seattle.  Of course, they may pop it somewhere else just to be unpredictable and to scare those whole felt 'safe' in the midwest/plains states.  North Korea having and maintaining nukes probably bumps that up to 80% to 90% probability.<br>
<br>
As a footnote, when I first woke up on Sept. 11th, for about 30 seconds, I thought someone had nuked NYC.  My mom comes in and tells me 'we're at war, someone attacked New York', and I almost ignore her, but I manage to turn my alarm clock, which was tuned to a news station, and it came on in the middle of a sentence of a reporter that said '...we've apparently lost all communication with the city.' in a really low, slow, serious tone.  Apparently he was talking about the cell network being clogged, but I was actually relieved to turn on the TV and see the WTC on fire.  <br>
<br>
Someday, my first assumption is going to be the correct one, and I dread that day. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=amourbien>Amourbien</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 71<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/4/03 10:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=219.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re: Hmmm</span><hr size=1> Saying that there is a 80-90% chance of a nuclear attack in the US is probably a bit misleading.  Estimates on any nuclear exchange occurring in the next ten years ranges from 30-60%.  This is quite a wide disparity, mainly dependant on with whom you speak to.  Of those that estimate an attack to occur close to 70% believe it will occur between Pakistan &amp; India.  The remaining 30% generally believe that a limited strike (i.e. terrorist) containing a dirty bomb (heavy doses of radiation, not necessarily explosive), or relatively weak nuclear bomb will occur in any number of targets (Israel, Washington DC, NYC, London).  The term relatively weak is also a bit misleading as it refers to Hiroshima-yields.  As we all know this would be more than enough to destroy the key sectors of any city.<br>
<br>
These estimates will always change as the world progresses forward.  It is important to not live in fear but be aware that the potential for great harm could exist.  I do not feel at this time North Korea has any intention on striking the US or any country, but is protecting itself so to speak from an attack by upping the ante.  It is a dangerous game to play, but every country that possesses these weapons understands that their use however limited would have disasterous affects upon themselves and the world at large.<br>
<br>
That said, I believe it highly unlikely within ten years there will be any strike against the US by a sovereign nation (my estimates are close to 0%).  A strike probability from a terrorist group against a US target though is different.  There are so many unknowns it is difficult to accurately assuage the figures.  When the Soviet Union collapsed, many of the Soviet scientists found themselves without much work/pay.  These people possessed the knoweldge, expertise, and often for the right price, the materials used to make such weapons.  Most of them understand the ethical nature of their work and despite economic hardships endure their lot in life.<br>
<br>
Throughout the 1990's there have been intercepts often in Eastern Europe by intelligence organisations of weapons grade plutonium, specialised parts for missile tubes, launch mechanisms, etc.  Once in a while you may hear of someone caught with a kilo of plutonium trying to smuggle it to Bulgaria or some other backwater.  There has been a notable difference in stockpiled materials in many plants that are unaccounted for.  The Soviets did have a poor system of accountancy by Western standards.  Nonetheless, it is assumed that at least some of the discrepancies have landed into &quot;foreign&quot; powers.  Be that meaning nations or groups of people no one knows.  <br>
<br>
That said (sorry this turned out much longer than I intended), it may or may not be likely that a nuclear detonation will occur in the US.  As Anika, and Ammelen have stated with their personal choice on locations to live, it is good perhaps to think like a terrorist.  If you were a terrorist what would you do?  I probably wouldn't attack Cincinnati, the surprise factor is definately a plus, but I would want to send a message.  The most likely US targets - Washington DC (seat of power for the entire US) especially at certain events when most of the leadership is present - namely the State of the Union address, NYC (financial capital of the world) destroy that and you basically muck up the entire worlds economy, LA (least likely target, entertainment capital of the world).  The rest of the nation is probably quite safe imo (from both national &amp; terrorist inspired nuclear warfare) so you have nothing to worry about - relatively <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
